{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 09:03:39.869715", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall OSPF control-plane and core/distribution/server connectivity are healthy.\n- The only abnormal behavior observed is that host_1_1_1_1 cannot reach its default gateway or any off-subnet destinations due to a Layer-3 misconfiguration: its IP/default gateway settings do not match the access segment it’s connected to.\n\nObserved symptoms\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.2.1.56/24, default via 10.2.1.1) cannot reach its default gateway or the server farm:\n  - Ping to 10.2.1.1 returns “Destination Host Unreachable” (source 10.2.1.56).\n  - Ping to 10.200.0.2/10.200.0.3 also fails with “Destination Host Unreachable.”\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.2/24, default via 10.2.1.1) has full end-to-end reachability:\n  - Pings DNS 10.200.0.2 and web server 10.200.0.3 successfully.\n  - Traceroute to 10.200.0.3 goes via 10.2.1.1 → 172.16.0.8 → 172.16.0.5 → 172.16.0.11 → 10.200.0.3, with low latency and no loss.\n- Distribution and server access devices can reach the server farm without issue.\n\nKey measurements and evidence\n- Host configurations:\n  - host_1_1_1_1:\n    - IP: 10.2.1.56/24; default route: via 10.2.1.1; resolv.conf nameserver 10.200.0.2.\n    - Ping 10.2.1.1: “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.2.1.56.\n    - Ping 10.200.0.2/10.200.0.3: all packets lost, “Destination Host Unreachable.”\n  - host_2_1_1_1:\n    - IP: 10.2.1.2/24; default route via 10.2.1.1.\n    - Ping 10.2.1.1: OK.\n    - Ping 10.200.0.2 and 10.200.0.3: OK.\n    - Traceroute 10.200.0.3: 5 hops, all reachable, RTT ~7 ms end-to-end.\n- Distribution device interfaces (L3 SVI/bridge IPs):\n  - switch_dist_1_1 br0: 10.1.1.1/24 (access domain for host_1_1_1_1).\n  - switch_dist_2_1 br0: 10.2.1.1/24 (access domain for host_2_1_1_1).\n- OSPF state and routing tables:\n  - OSPF adjacencies up across core, distribution, and server access. Core_1 and core_2 are ABRs for area 0.0.0.1 to area 0.\n  - All routers have routes to 10.200.0.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 via expected next-hops.\n  - switch_dist_1_1 and switch_dist_2_1 can ping 10.200.0.3 successfully (low RTTs), indicating healthy inter-area reachability.\n\nAnomaly detection\n- Host-side anomaly: host_1_1_1_1 is configured in subnet 10.2.1.0/24 with default gateway 10.2.1.1, but it is connected to the access domain whose L3 interface is 10.1.1.1/24 (switch_dist_1_1 br0).\n- Classic symptom: “Destination Host Unreachable” sourced by the host itself when pinging its supposed gateway indicates ARP resolution failure for the configured gateway on the local L2 segment. Since 10.2.1.1 does not exist on that segment, the host cannot reach any off-link destinations.\n\nFault localization\n- The fault is localized to host_1_1_1_1’s Layer-3 configuration relative to its access segment.\n- Network devices (switch_dist_1_1, switch_dist_2_1, core routers, server-access, and servers) show normal OSPF operation and correct routing. End-to-end connectivity is validated from properly addressed host_2_1_1_1 and from distribution routers.\n\nRoot cause\n- host_1_1_1_1 is mis-addressed for its physical attachment. It resides on the access network behind switch_dist_1_1, whose interface is 10.1.1.1/24, but host_1_1_1_1 is statically configured in 10.2.1.0/24 with a default gateway of 10.2.1.1. This L3 mismatch prevents local gateway reachability and blocks all routed traffic from that host.\n\nImpact assessment\n- Impact is confined to host_1_1_1_1; host_2_1_1_1 and all servers are operating normally and are mutually reachable.\n- DNS and web services in 10.200.0.0/24 are reachable from the rest of the network as expected.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17432, "output_tokens": 3221, "total_tokens": 20653, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16896}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2048}}}
